SIMPLE: scab
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Scab
<hw>Scab</hw> <pr>(sk⟦acr⟧b)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>scab</ets>, <ets>scabbe</ets>, <ets>shabbe</ets>; cf. AS. <ets>scaeb</ets>, <ets>sceabb</ets>, <ets>scebb</ets>, Dan. & Sw. <ets>skab</ets>, and also L. <ets>scabies</ets>, fr. <ets>scabere</ets> to scratch, akin to E. <ets>shave</ets>. See <er>Shave</er>, and cf. <er>Shab</er>, <er>Shabby</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An incrustation over a sore, wound, vesicle, or pustule, formed by the drying up of the discharge from the diseased part.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The itch in man; also, the scurvy.</def> <mark>[Colloq. or Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The mange, esp. when it appears on sheep.</def> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A disease of potatoes producing pits in their surface, caused by a minute fungus (<spn>Tiburcinia Scabies</spn>).</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Founding)</fld> <def>A slight irregular protuberance which defaces the surface of a casting, caused by the breaking away of a part of the mold.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A mean, dirty, paltry fellow.</def> <mark>[Low]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>A nickname for a workman who engages for lower wages than are fixed by the trades unions; also, for one who takes the place of a workman on a strike.</def> <mark>[Cant]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Any one of various more or less destructive fungus diseases attacking cultivated plants, and usually forming dark-colored crustlike spots.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scab</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Scab
<hw>Scab</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Scabbed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Scabbing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To become covered with a scab; <as>as, the wound <ex>scabbed</ex> over</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>to take the place of a striking worker.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scabbard</ent>⟦br⟧
